396 The states reflects three different life cycles for three

398 Prepared statement: STMT_INITIALIZED -> STMT_PREPARED -> STMT_EXECUTED.
399 Stored procedure: STMT_INITIALIZED_FOR_SP -> STMT_EXECUTED.
400 Other statements: STMT_REGULAR_EXECUTION never changes.
401 */
402 enum enum_state {
403 STMT_INITIALIZED = 0,

411 /*
412 State and state changes in SP:

678 /*
679 Enum enum_locked_tables_mode and locked_tables_mode member are
680 used to indicate whether the so-called "locked tables mode" is on,
681 and what kind of mode is active.
682
683 Locked tables mode is used when it's necessary to open and
684 lock many tables at once, for usage across multiple
685 (sub-)statements.
686 This may be necessary either for queries that use stored functions
687 and triggers, in which case the statements inside functions and
688 triggers may be executed many times, or for implementation of
689 LOCK TABLES, in which case the opened tables are reused by all
690 subsequent statements until a call to UNLOCK TABLES.
691
692 The kind of locked tables mode employed for stored functions and
693 triggers is also called "prelocked mode".
694 In this mode, first open_tables() call to open the tables used
695 in a statement analyses all functions used by the statement
696 and adds all indirectly used tables to the list of tables to
697 open and lock.
698 It also marks the parse tree of the statement as requiring
699 prelocking. After that, lock_tables() locks the entire list
700 of tables and changes THD::locked_tables_modeto LTM_PRELOCKED.
701 All statements executed inside functions or triggers
702 use the prelocked tables, instead of opening their own ones.
703 Prelocked mode is turned off automatically once close_thread_tables()
704 of the main statement is called.
705 */

2542 similar to ROW_COUNT member of the GET DIAGNOSTICS stack of the SQL
2543 standard (see SQL99, part 2, search for ROW_COUNT). Its value is
2544 implementation defined for anything except INSERT, DELETE, UPDATE.
2545
2546 ROW_COUNT is assigned according to the following rules:
2547
2548 - In my_ok():

2550 - for DDL statements: to 0.
2551

2553

2555 java.sql.Statement.getUpdateCount() is defined to (sic) "return the
2556 current result as an update count; if the result is a ResultSet

2560 MySQL ODBC driver.
2561
2562 - For SIGNAL statements: to 0 per WL#2110 specification (see also
2563 sql_signal.cc comment). Zero is used since that's the "default"
2564 value of ROW_COUNT in the Diagnostics Area.
2565 */

3774 /**
3775 The GTID of the currently owned transaction.
3776
3777 ==== Modes of ownership ====
3778
3779 The following modes of ownership are possible:
3780
3781 - owned_gtid.sidno==0: the thread does not own any transaction.
3782
3783 - owned_gtid.sidno==THD::OWNED_SIDNO_ANONYMOUS(==-2): the thread
3784 owns an anonymous transaction
3785
3786 - owned_gtid.sidno>0 and owned_gtid.gno>0: the thread owns a GTID
3787 transaction.
3788
3789 - (owned_gtid.sidno==THD::OWNED_SIDNO_GTID_SET(==-1): this is
3790 currently not used. It was reserved for the case where multiple
3791 GTIDs are owned (using gtid_next_list). This was one idea to
3792 make GTIDs work with NDB: due to the epoch concept, multiple
3793 transactions can be combined into one in NDB, and therefore a
3794 single transaction on a slave can have multiple GTIDs.)
3795
3796 ==== Life cycle of ownership ====
3797
3798 Generally, transaction ownership starts when the transaction is
3799 assigned its GTID and ends when the transaction commits or rolls
3800 back. On a master (GTID_NEXT=AUTOMATIC), the GTID is assigned
3801 just before binlog flush; on a slave (GTID_NEXT=UUID:NUMBER or
3802 GTID_NEXT=ANONYMOUS) it is assigned before starting the
3803 transaction.
3804
3805 A new client always starts with owned_gtid.sidno=0.
3806
3807 Ownership can be acquired in the following ways:
3808
3809 A1. If GTID_NEXT = 'AUTOMATIC' and GTID_MODE = OFF/OFF_PERMISSIVE:
3810 The thread acquires anonymous ownership in
3811 gtid_state->generate_automatic_gtid called from
3812 MYSQL_BIN_LOG::write_transaction.
3813
3814 A2. If GTID_NEXT = 'AUTOMATIC' and GTID_MODE = ON/ON_PERMISSIVE:
3815 The thread generates the GTID and acquires ownership in
3816 gtid_state->generate_automatic_gtid called from
3817 MYSQL_BIN_LOG::write_transaction.
3818
3819 A3. If GTID_NEXT = 'UUID:NUMBER': The thread acquires ownership in
3820 the following ways:
3821
3822 - In a client, the SET GTID_NEXT statement acquires ownership.
3823
3824 - The slave's analogy to a clients SET GTID_NEXT statement is
3825 Gtid_log_event::do_apply_event. So the slave acquires
3826 ownership in this function.
3827
3828 Note: if the GTID UUID:NUMBER is already included in
3829 GTID_EXECUTED, then the transaction must be skipped (the GTID
3830 auto-skip feature). Thus, ownership is *not* acquired in this
3831 case and owned_gtid.sidno==0.
3832
3833 A4. If GTID_NEXT = 'ANONYMOUS':
3834
3835 - In a client, the SET GTID_NEXT statement acquires ownership.
3836
3837 - In a slave thread, Gtid_log_event::do_apply_event acquires
3838 ownership.
3839
3840 - Contrary to the case of GTID_NEXT='UUID:NUMBER', it is
3841 allowed to execute two transactions in sequence without
3842 changing GTID_NEXT (cf. R1 and R2 below). Both transactions
3843 should be executed as anonymous transactions. But ownership
3844 is released when the first transaction commits. Therefore,
3845 when GTID_NEXT='ANONYMOUS', we also acquire anonymous
3846 ownership when starting to execute a statement, in
3847 gtid_reacquire_ownership_if_anonymous called from
3848 gtid_pre_statement_checks (usually called from
3849 mysql_execute_command).
3850
3851 A5. Slave applier threads start in a special mode, having
3852 GTID_NEXT='NOT_YET_DETERMINED'. This mode cannot be set in a
3853 regular client. When GTID_NEXT=NOT_YET_DETERMINED, the slave
3854 thread is postponing the decision of the value of GTID_NEXT
3855 until it has more information. There are three cases:
3856
3857 - If the first transaction of the relay log has a
3858 Gtid_log_event, then it will set GTID_NEXT=GTID:NUMBER and
3859 acquire GTID ownership in Gtid_log_event::do_apply_event.
3860
3861 - If the first transaction of the relay log has a
3862 Anonymous_gtid_log_event, then it will set
3863 GTID_NEXT=ANONYMOUS and acquire anonymous ownership in
3864 Gtid_log_event::do_apply_event.
3865
3866 - If the relay log was received from a pre-5.7.6 master with
3867 GTID_MODE=OFF (or a pre-5.6 master), then there are neither
3868 Gtid_log_events nor Anonymous_log_events in the relay log.
3869 In this case, the slave sets GTID_NEXT=ANONYMOUS and
3870 acquires anonymous ownership when executing a
3871 Query_log_event (Query_log_event::do_apply_event calls
3872 dispatch_sql_command which calls gtid_pre_statement_checks which
3873 calls gtid_reacquire_ownership_if_anonymous).
3874
3875 Ownership is released in the following ways:
3876
3877 R1. A thread that holds GTID ownership releases ownership at
3878 transaction commit or rollback. If GTID_NEXT=AUTOMATIC, all
3879 is fine. If GTID_NEXT=UUID:NUMBER, the UUID:NUMBER cannot be
3880 used for another transaction, since only one transaction can
3881 have any given GTID. To avoid the user mistake of forgetting
3882 to set back GTID_NEXT, on commit we set
3883 thd->variables.gtid_next.type=UNDEFINED_GTID. Then, any
3884 statement that user tries to execute other than SET GTID_NEXT
3885 will generate an error.
3886
3887 R2. A thread that holds anonymous ownership releases ownership at
3888 transaction commit or rollback. In this case there is no harm
3889 in leaving GTID_NEXT='ANONYMOUS', so
3890 thd->variables.gtid_next.type will remain ANONYMOUS_GTID and
3891 not UNDEFINED_GTID.
3892
3893 There are statements that generate multiple transactions in the
3894 binary log. This includes the following:
3895
3896 M1. DROP TABLE that is used with multiple tables, and the tables
3897 belong to more than one of the following groups: non-temporary
3898 table, temporary transactional table, temporary
3899 non-transactional table. DROP TABLE is split into one
3900 transaction for each of these groups of tables.
3901
3902 M2. DROP DATABASE that fails e.g. because rmdir fails. Then a
3903 single DROP TABLE is generated, which lists all tables that
3904 were dropped before the failure happened. But if the list of
3905 tables is big, and grows over a limit, the statement will be
3906 split into multiple statements.
3907
3908 M3. CREATE TABLE ... SELECT that is logged in row format. Then
3909 the server generates a single CREATE statement, followed by a
3910 BEGIN ... row events ... COMMIT transaction.
3911
3912 M4. A statement that updates both transactional and
3913 non-transactional tables in the same statement, and is logged
3914 in row format. Then it generates one transaction for the
3915 non-transactional row updates, followed by one transaction for
3916 the transactional row updates.
3917
3918 M5. CALL is executed as multiple transactions and logged as
3919 multiple transactions.
3920
3921 The general rules for multi-transaction statements are:
3922
3923 - If GTID_NEXT=AUTOMATIC and GTID_MODE=ON or ON_PERMISSIVE, one
3924 GTID should be generated for each transaction within the
3925 statement. Therefore, ownership must be released after each
3926 commit so that a new GTID can be generated by the next
3927 transaction. Typically mysql_bin_log.commit() is called to
3928 achieve this. (Note that some of these statements are currently
3929 disallowed when GTID_MODE=ON.)
3930
3931 - If GTID_NEXT=AUTOMATIC and GTID_MODE=OFF or OFF_PERMISSIVE, one
3932 Anonymous_gtid_log_event should be generated for each
3933 transaction within the statement. Similar to the case above, we
3934 call mysql_bin_log.commit() and release ownership between
3935 transactions within the statement.
3936
3937 This works for all the special cases M1-M5 except M4. When a
3938 statement writes both non-transactional and transactional
3939 updates to the binary log, both the transaction cache and the
3940 statement cache are flushed within the same call to
3941 flush_thread_caches(THD) from within the binary log group commit
3942 code. At that point we cannot use mysql_bin_log.commit().
3943 Instead we release ownership using direct calls to
3944 gtid_state->release_anonymous_ownership() and
3945 thd->clear_owned_gtids() from binlog_cache_mngr::flush.
3946
3947 - If GTID_NEXT=ANONYMOUS, anonymous ownership must be *preserved*
3948 between transactions within the statement, to prevent that a
3949 concurrent SET GTID_MODE=ON makes it impossible to log the
3950 statement. To avoid that ownership is released if
3951 mysql_bin_log.commit() is called, we set
3952 thd->is_commit_in_middle_of_statement before calling
3953 mysql_bin_log.commit. Note that we must set this flag only if
3954 GTID_NEXT=ANONYMOUS, not if the transaction is anonymous when
3955 GTID_NEXT=AUTOMATIC and GTID_MODE=OFF.
3956
3957 This works for all the special cases M1-M5 except M4. When a
3958 statement writes non-transactional updates in the middle of a
3959 transaction, but keeps some transactional updates in the
3960 transaction cache, then it is not easy to know at the time of
3961 calling mysql_bin_log.commit() whether anonymous ownership needs
3962 to be preserved or not. Instead, we directly check if the
3963 transaction cache is nonempty before releasing anonymous
3964 ownership inside Gtid_state::update_gtids_impl.
3965
3966 - If GTID_NEXT='UUID:NUMBER', it is impossible to log a
3967 multi-transaction statement, since each GTID can only be used by
3968 one transaction. Therefore, an error must be generated in this
3969 case. Errors are generated in different ways for the different
3970 statement types:
3971
3972 - DROP TABLE: we can detect the situation before it happens,
3973 since the table type is known once the tables are opened. So
3974 we generate an error before even executing the statement.
3975
3976 - DROP DATABASE: we can't detect the situation until it is too
3977 late; the tables have already been dropped and we cannot log
3978 anything meaningful. So we don't log at all.
3979
3980 - CREATE TABLE ... SELECT: this is not allowed when
3981 enforce_gtid_consistency is ON; the statement will be
3982 forbidden in is_ddl_gtid_compatible.
3983
3984 - Statements that update both transactional and
3985 non-transactional tables are disallowed when GTID_MODE=ON, so
3986 this normally does not happen. However, it can happen if the
3987 slave uses a different engine type than the master, so that a
3988 statement that updates InnoDB+InnoDB on master updates
3989 InnoDB+MyISAM on slave. In this case the statement will be
3990 forbidden in is_dml_gtid_compatible and will not be allowed to
3991 execute.
3992
3993 - CALL: the second statement will generate an error because
3994 GTID_NEXT is 'undefined'. Note that this situation can only
3995 happen if user does it on purpose: A CALL on master is logged
3996 as multiple statements, so a slave never executes CALL with
3997 GTID_NEXT='UUID:NUMBER'.
3998
3999 Finally, ownership release is suppressed in one more corner case:
4000
4001 C1. Administration statements including OPTIMIZE TABLE, REPAIR
4002 TABLE, or ANALYZE TABLE are written to the binary log even if
4003 they fail. This means that the thread first calls
4004 trans_rollack, and then writes the statement to the binlog.
4005 Rollback normally releases ownership. But ownership must be
4006 kept until writing the binlog. The solution is that these
4007 statements set thd->skip_gtid_rollback=true before calling
4008 trans_rollback, and Gtid_state::update_on_rollback does not
4009 release ownership if the flag is set.
4010
4011 @todo It would probably be better to encapsulate this more, maybe
4012 use Gtid_specification instead of Gtid.
4013 */

4561 (e.g. duplicated GTIDs) and as such are forbidden:
4562

4565

4744 /*
4745 Send the status of the current statement execution over network.
4746
4747 In MySQL, there are two types of SQL statements: those that return
4748 a result set and those that return status information only.
4749
4750 If a statement returns a result set, it consists of 3 parts:
4751 - result set meta-data
4752 - variable number of result set rows (can be 0)
4753 - followed and terminated by EOF or ERROR packet
4754
4755 Once the client has seen the meta-data information, it always
4756 expects an EOF or ERROR to terminate the result set. If ERROR is
4757 received, the result set rows are normally discarded (this is up
4758 to the client implementation, libmysql at least does discard them).
4759 EOF, on the contrary, means "successfully evaluated the entire
4760 result set". Since we don't know how many rows belong to a result
4761 set until it's evaluated, EOF/ERROR is the indicator of the end
4762 of the row stream. Note, that we can not buffer result set rows
4763 on the server -- there may be an arbitrary number of rows. But
4764 we do buffer the last packet (EOF/ERROR) in the Diagnostics_area and
4765 delay sending it till the very end of execution (here), to be able to
4766 change EOF to an ERROR if commit failed or some other error occurred
4767 during the last cleanup steps taken after execution.
4768
4769 A statement that does not return a result set doesn't send result
4770 set meta-data either. Instead it returns one of:
4771 - OK packet
4772 - ERROR packet.
4773 Similarly to the EOF/ERROR of the previous statement type, OK/ERROR
4774 packet is "buffered" in the Diagnostics Area and sent to the client
4775 in the end of statement.
4776
4777 @note This method defines a template, but delegates actual
4778 sending of data to virtual Protocol::send_{ok,eof,error}. This
4779 allows for implementation of protocols that "intercept" ok/eof/error
4780 messages, and store them in memory, etc, instead of sending to
4781 the client.
4782
4783 @pre The Diagnostics Area is assigned or disabled. It can not be empty
4784 -- we assume that every SQL statement or COM_* command
4785 generates OK, ERROR, or EOF status.
4786
4787 @post The status information is encoded to protocol format and sent to the
4788 client.
4789
4790 @return We conventionally return void, since the only type of error
4791 that can happen here is a NET (transport) error, and that one
4792 will become visible when we attempt to read from the NET the
4793 next command.
4794 Diagnostics_area::is_sent is set for debugging purposes only.
4795 */
4796
4797 void send_statement_status();
